                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Lüġatnama</summary>
                        <textLang mainLang="ota" otherLangs="lat gre chg arm ukr ron">Ottoman
                            Turkish, Latin, Greek, Chaghatay, Armenian, Ukrainian, and
                            Romanian</textLang>
                        <msItem xml:id="MS_Marsh_187-item1" n="1">
                            <title key="">Lüġatnama</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ota" key="">لغات نامه</title>
                            <note>A comparative vocabulary of Latin, Modern Greek, Ottoman Turkish,
                                Chaghatay (described as "Tatarice"), Armenian, archaic Ukranian
                                (described as "Slavonice seu Russice", and Romanian words arranged
                                in seven columns, beginning with Latin on the left side, and
                                concluding with Romanian on the right. In some places the Greek is
                                omitted. The Latin words only are arranged in alphabetical
                                order.</note>
                            <note>The MS was clearly commissioned by a Western scholar (perhaps
                                    <persName xml:id="person_10605557" role="fmo">Jacob van
                                    Gool</persName>) who wanted to supplement his edition of
                                Calepinus with six languages not in the original. The Latin of the
                                first column is therefore primary, and the scribe evidently had the
                                printed book before him, as there is occasional evidence of
                                influence from the Polish of Calepinus on the Ukrainian of the MS.
                                He seems to have been most at home in Modern Greek and Ottoman
                                Turkish; perhaps a Greek from Asia Minor. The Armenian, Ukrainian,
                                Romanian, and Chaghatay columns are not the work of a native
                                speaker, as they all display a mixture of dialect forms, suggesting
                                that the writer had obtained them from a number of different
                                informants. The note "ex diversis lexicographis, oreque Turc. Arm.
                                Graec. compositus" seems to imply consulting various informants, if
                                whoever wrote it actually knew anything about the MS's origins.
                                Grammatically, the Ukrainian and Armenian could not have been
                                written by anyone who spoke the language as his own.</note>
